summaries.title: Leadership and Mentorship in Engineering Design Projects
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah described how leading senior design teams strengthened her confidence in project management and technical problem-solving. She reflected on mentorship as a core component of her academic identity, often supporting younger women of color navigating engineering culture. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Community and Peer Mentorship as Anchors
summaries.summaryText: Peer mentors and cultural centers helped Luis navigate isolation as a first-gen Latino student. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Recognizing Privilege and Peer Disparities in Engineering Education
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Research and Cultural Expectations
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Transition from High School to University-Level Engineering
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Navigating Gender Bias in Research Environments
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 4/4]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Maria’s sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 3]

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didn’t even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria describing her initial confusion with academic expectations as a first-gen student.

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Aaliyah on the value of mentorship networks.

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Aaliyah on the value of mentorship networks.

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didn’t even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria describing her initial confusion with academic expectations as a first-gen student.

quotes.quoteText: When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasn’t just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Ethan on the value of diverse collaboration.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Priya describing family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: I realized I had access to engineering summer camps that most of my friends never even heard of — that’s when privilege clicked for me. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Ethan reflecting on his exposure to early STEM opportunities.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria discussing gaps in support infrastructure.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Aaliyah describing the advocacy work tied to her leadership role.

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on parental expectations and emotional weight of being first-gen.

quotes.quoteText: My parents say, ‘Just do your best,’ but I can tell they really mean, ‘Don’t waste this chance we gave you.’ [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on implicit cultural pressure from family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on peer support and cultural representation.

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Encourage faculty to include ‘learning journeys’ in course introductions
Develop short workshops on inclusive teaching practices

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria
